{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657384/1923092301/0568.xml":{"full_text":"State Primaries Show Pinchot\nHe Will Have Fight at Home\nGovernor Still Silent on Candidacy,\nFinds Food for Thought in De\nfeat of His Henchmen\nHarrisburg, Pa.. September 22.\n\u201c-Primary elections In Pennsylvania\nTuesday mean Gov\u2019/ Clifford Pinchot*\nmay have to fight for delegates to\nthe next republican national conven\ntion In event he determines to ask\nthe support of the state for the presi\ndency. The governor has been on a\nfishing trip the last few days gnd\nlabor leaders and others who have\nteen urging him to consider being a\ncandidate do not know much more\nthan a week ago. It is evident,\nhowever primary results in counties\ntvhere tno governor took a hand to\nchastise men who had opposed his\nleglslatlto program or where he\nDucked one faction of his supoorters\nagainst another have given Sir. Pln-\nCOot food for thought.\nThe go\\ernor stayed out. of the\nPhiladelphia fight, but got into\nothers, very largely through use of\nhis name and consequently those\nwho resent mention of his name for\nPresident on general principles, the\nmen smarting from legislative con\ntroversies and the anti-prohibition\nelement have been at work to make\nthe most of conditions. The gov\nernor Is expected back In the capital\nthe middle of next week, but the be\nlief continues here that he will main\ntain his position of awaiting devel\nopments and avoid committing him\nself.\nSenators Pepper and Reed put into\ntheir statement what a good manv\ncounty leaders and influential legis\nlators had been thinking. But in\nview of the fact Secretary Mellon is\ngenerally thought to be desirous of'\nhaving the delegation from his home\nstate favorable to the President and\nthat certain primary results are the\nsubject of wide comment something\nmore definite than the mere observa\ntion that it is unwise at this time\nto say much may be expected before\nlong. k\nThere is no doubt, judging from\nBAKER MENTIONED\nAS OHIO GOVERNOR\n\nFormer War Secretary May\nBe Primary Opponent of\ni Donahey, Is Said.\n\nSpeciil Dispatch to The Star. i\nCOLUMBUS, Ohio, September 22.\nFollowing the departure of former\nSecretary of War Newton D. Baker\nfor Europe there has developed a\nlittle boom for him for the demo\ncratic nomination for governor next i\nyear. Last year when the democrats j\nopposed to the nomination of Gov.\nDonahey were looking for a candi\ndate Secretary Baker's name was\nsuggested. It did not meet with j\nany marked enthusiasm, and the I\nDonahey opposition finally' crystal- I\nJzed about Judge James Johnson of i\nthe supreme court.\nIn the regular campaign the Cleve- j\nland organization ostensibly sup-\nported the Donahey ticket, but in fact\ntook little interest in the contest.\nEvidently Secretary Baker's opinion\nof Gov. Donahey has not changed I\nsince then, and around him and the t\nCleveland democratic organization\nwill center opposition to renomina-\nlion of the governor next year, i\nMore likely, however. >the anti-Don- j\nahey democrats will select another}\ncandidate, and just now George\nWhite, former congressman from the\nfifteenth district and manager of\nC?ov. Cox's campaign in 1320. seems\nto be favored. A brief statement\nfrom Mr. White at his home in\nMarietta indicated he was thinking\nof the nomination. It seems quite\ncertain now that the governor will\nnot be given an uncontested nomina\ntion for a second term.\nDurbin Denies Rumor.\nState Chairman W. W. Durbin of\nthe democratic state committee vig\norously denied a report published\nhere last week that because of ill\nhealth he might not remain at the\nhead of the committee.\nThis indication thaKChairman Dur\nbin, who squarely broke with the gov\nernor two months ago over patronage\nmatters, does not propose to be de\nposed. is specially interesting in view\nof the preparations qf the antt-Dona\nhey democrats to oppose him in the\nprimaries. The situation is rather\nthreatening for the democrats of Ohio\nwith the national campaign upon\nthem. It seems Gov. Donahey should I\nbe able to defeat attempts to unhorse\nhim with but a single term, for he\nis popular with the rank and file of\nthe party, and may depend upon help\nfrom republicans should the occasion\ndemand.\nThe declaration of war upon W. O.\nMcAdoo made by former Senator At\nlee Pomerene last week, carrying with\nIt. as It seems, the intention of the\nsenator to fight Mr. McAdoo's presi\ndential nomination aspirations, has\nnot caused much of a flurry in Ohio,\nprobably for the reason that It was\nnot expected that the McAdoo forces\nwould make any effort to secure dele\ngates in this state. Gov. Cox being\na candidate for the presidential nom-.\ninatlon again\u2014and it seems to be\ngenerally assumed here that he will\u2014\nwill have the solid delegation from\nhis state. Nevertheless Mr. McAdoo\nstands high with the Ohio democrats,\nand with Mr. Cox out of it, probably\nwould receive considerable support\nfrom Ohio. Though nothing has been\nsaid yet about the Ohio delegates at\nlarge to the democratic national con\nvention, it would be unusual If Sen\nator Pomerene should be omitted. He\ni will be given the opportunity In all\nprobability of opposing Mr. McAdoo\nIf he wishes to do so.\nNew G. O. P. Candidate.\nAnother candidate for the repub\nlican nomination for governor Is ex\npected to enter the already large\nfield in a few days. He is former\nSpeaker of the Ohio House Rupert\nP. Beetham of Cadis.\nThe republican leaders, who fear\nthat former Gov. H. L. Davis would\npot make a strong candidate at the\npolls, see In this large and growing\nfield of candidates for their nomi\nnation for governor danger that he\nmay land the nomination, for he has\na certain strong organization that\ncannot ,Jdc shaken from him., and\nwith U\\e balance of the vote spilt up\nbetween a half dozen other candi\ndates. he might ride Into the nomi\nnation. The feeling Is that Gov.\nDonahey. unpopular as he evidently j\nIs with the organization democrats,\nwould probably be able to defeat\nDavis.\nCol. Carml A. Thompson is still\nwithout expression as to his atti\ntude toward the nomination for gov\nernor next year, though he began\nmaking a canvass of the state with\na view to ascertaining the sentiment\nof the ifarty toward him. Just now\nbe is working hard to advance the\nchances of his city, Cleveland, for\ngetting the republican i.Aiional con-\nL x-entlon. The Cleveland workers do\nA not seem to be at all discouraged at\nnot obtaining the approval at Presl-\nA dent Coolldge for their enterprise.\nEvidently if he has not been able\nto stand for them, he has assured\nthem that he will do nothing against\nA them. 4. H. GALBRAITH.\nBk v>\nwhat men here on state capltol busi\nness' have to say, that satisfaction\nwith the Preslden is growing among\nthe rank and file of the republicans\nof Pennsylvania and that prospects of\nan Increase of price of anthracite\nhave dimmed gratification at the\ngovernor's success In putting opera\ntors and miners to a truce for two\nyears. On the other hand there Is no\nquestion but what the governor has\nwon much commendation by the\nvigorous manner In which he went\nabout reorganization of the state\ngovernment and by forecasts of a\nlegislative program for 1925. which\nwould include means to supervise\ncoal mining and distribution book\nkeeping, ballot reforms and other\nthings. The very fact there Is a\npopular interest in his capltol hill\nplans might handicap him in entering\na presidential race.\nCoal Action Has Weight.\nAnother factor which may weigh\nwith the governor Is the manner In\nwhich governors of other states take\nup his campaign to prevent the in\ncreased cost of anthracite being\npassed on to consumers. Already\nseveral governors have come back at\nhis proposals for joint action with the\nsuggestion that Pennsylvania repeal\nthe anthracite tonnage tax.\nOver against all these matters are\nurgings from people in various states\nto become a candidate and the 'offers\nof support from various groups in\nPennsylvania who are eager to have\nMr. Pinchot ask for the delegation\nfrom his own state. Certain of these\npeople would also like to be in the\ndelegation.\nOne of the noticeable features of\nthe primary elections from a demo\ncratic standpoint was that Judge\nEugene C. Bonnlwell, who will be a\ncandidate for the democratic national\ncommittee, got the highest vote for\nthe municipal court In Philadelphia,\nbeing on both republican and demo\ncratic tickets. The democratic situa\ntion, however, has been lost sight of\nIn the speculation as to presidential\npossibilities.\nA. BOYD HAMILTON.\nFORD WINS BACKING\nIN SOUTH DAKOTA\n\nDemocrats in State Near\nSplit, One Faction Is Sup\nporting McAdoo.\n1 Spee'al Dispatch to The Star.\nSIOUX FALLS. S. D.. September 22.\n\u2014lt now seems assured that South\nDakota will be the scene of a battle\nroyal between democratic supporters\nof Henry Ford for President and\ni those who favor William G. McAdoo\nj In the presidential campaign of 1924.\nThe South Dakota democratic faction,\nof which E. S. Johnson of Yank\nton. former United States senator, is\nlone of the leaders, favors Mr. Me-\nI Adoo.\nI That the McAdoo supporters will\nj have opposition now is certain, as\nj State Senator Eric J. Ellefson of\nI Sioux Falla, one of the democratic j\nj leaders in the last session of the\nSouth Dakota legislature, has be\ncome a candidate for nomination for\nI governor, and in his announcement\nstates that he is for Henry Ford for\npresident. He will make an aggres\n-1 sive fight to have the South Dakota\ndelegation pledged to Ford.\nWin* Magnus Johnson.\nJ What adds more than ordinary im\nj portanoe to the declaration of Sen- I\nj ator Ellefson is the report received J\nhere from Minnesota that Senator\n1 Ellefson or some one representing I\nhim recently held a conference with j\nI United States Senator Magnus John\n-1 son of Minnesota, and that as the re- 1\nI suit of the conference Senator John- 1\nson and other Johnson leaders prom-\nised that when the critical time In\nSenator Ellefson\u2019s campaign for the\ngovernorship came they would send\nspeakers to South Dakota to boost his\ncandidacy.\nIt is assumed that the democratic\nfaction which opposes Mr. Ffird and\nwhich favors Mr. McAdoo will lose i\nno time In accepting the challenge Is\nsued by Senator Ellefson.\nSenator Ellefson during the last\nsession of the state legislature prov\ned himself an astute politician, but in\nthe ranks of the democrats who es\npouse the cause of Mr. McAdoo In\nSouth Dakota are democratic vet\nerans who know the political game\nfrom start to finish, and who ex\npress no fear that when the proper\ntime comes they can capture\nSouth Dakota delegation.\nALFRED BURKHOLDER.\nSENATOR MOSES\u2019 NEW\n.POSITION ATTACKED\nNew Hampshire G. 0. P. Ques\ntions Alleged Desertion of Hiram\nJohnson for Coolidge Boom.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nMANCHESTER. N. H,, September 22.\n\u2014Prominent republicans In New\nHampshire are criticizing United\nStates Senator George H. Moses for\nflopping from his advocacy of Hi\nram Johnson of California as the\nlogical choice for the republican nom\nination for President in 1924 to the\nstandard of Calvin Coolldge.\nHenry H. Metcalf of Concord, In a\neditor of the Concord\nMonitor Patriot asks Senator Moses\nfor an explanation. To quote Mr.\nMetcalf\u2019s letter, \"a good many people\nwould like to know the explanation\nof Senator Moses\u2019 right-about-face.\nIt has been contended by some of his\nfriends that he is a man of firm con\nvtctlons and stands by them, regard\nless of consequences. His recent con\nduct, however, does not seem to sus\ntain,. this contention. It would seem\nto the average mind that he has\nclimbed aboard the Coolidge' \u2018band\nwagon,\u2019 (as ex-Gov. John H. Bart\nlett Is reported to have put It) as a\nmatter of personal expediency, en\ntirely regardless of principle or con\nviction. Yet It may be possible that\nhe has changed his mind and now fa\nvors the Harding policies, which he\nformerly despised, but which Coolldge\npromises religiously to carry out.\nHe may. like Saul of Tarsus, sud\ndenly have seen new light, and come\nfervently to lore what he formerly\nI hated. Until some explanation is\nvouchsafed by the senator, or some\nauthorized spokesman, It will remain\na question whether he has been act\ning from principle or expediency In\nhis recent political genuflections.\u201d\nIn tne democratic party ranks of\nNew Hampshire, leaders are watch\ning with Interest the scramble among\nleading democrats of Manchester for\nthe nomination for mayor. There are\nsix candidates seeking the honor and\nthe strong labor vote, upon which the\ndemocrats count, may be split\nthroughout the state, as a result of\nthe battle in Manchester.\nj. j. McCarthy.\nThere are two railroad systems In\nthe Philippines with a total mileage\nof about 80#.\nc\nTHE SUNDAY STAR, WASHINGTON, D. C., SEPTEMBER 23,. 1923-PART .I.\nCONNECTICUT GIF.\nBACKING COOLIDGE\nParty Leaders Fall Into Line\nand Solid Delegation at\nConvention Is Seen.\nSpecial. Dispatch to The Star.\nHARTFORD, Conn.. September 22.\nThe announcemnet of the tentative\nplan of the republican national com\nmittee for representation In the na\ntional convention of 1924, by which\nConnecticut republicans hope to get\ntwo more delegates, increasing the\nstate delegation from fourteen to\nulxtoen. has given Impetus to the In\nterest In the make-up of that dele\ngation. Republicans are getting\nready to shy their hats Into the ring\nas candidates for delegates and the\nindication that the nominee for the\npresidency will be from a New Eng\nland state is an additional reason\nwhy Connecticut republicans want to\nto the convention.\nThere seems now little doubt that\nConnecticut will send a solid Cool\nidge delegation to the convention.\nLeaders have indicated definitely\nwhere they stand. It Is significant\nthau Lieut. Gov. Hiram Bingham of\nNew Haven, almost certain to be the\nrepublican nominee for governor\nnext year, is one of the most out\nspoken advocates of President Cool\nidge. In a speech at a recent dinner\noi the West Haven republican organ\nization Mr. Bingham paid high\ntribute to President Coolldge.\nDemocrats are much In the same\nas were the republicans In\n19-0, with no candidate who has any\nthing like united support, although\nit goes without saying that Homer\nCummings of Stamford, member of\nthe democratic national committee,\ncan have Connecticut\u2019s vote as a\nfavorite son,\u2019\u2019 but this complimen\ntary vote would be likelv to divide\namong the real candidates without\nmuch delay. As far as the state'\nticket is concerned the democrats are\nlikely to have a new line-up and the\nmost probable candidate to run\nagainst Lieut. Gov Bingham for gov\nernor Is William E. Thoms, fonner\nmayor of Waterbury.\nH. I. HORTON.\nWYOMING gToT. HEAD\nSEES 1924 VICTORY\nReduction of Expenses and Gen\neral Prosperity Will Mean\nSweep, Spencer Declares.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nCHEYENNE. Wyo.. September 22.\nRepublicans In the east are confident\nof another sweeping victory In 1924,\nState Chairman P. C. Spencer found\non his trip to Washington. After\nconferring with President Calvin\nCoolldge. National Chairman John T.\nAdams. George B. Lockwood, secre\ntary of the national committee and\neditor of the National Republican:\nWilliam C. Demlng, president of the\nUnited States Civil Service Commis\nsion. and others, the head of the\nyomlng G. O. P. came awav con\nvinced that If the west can keep\nUp with the east there will be no\ndoubt about next year\u2019s result.\n\"Return of prosperity, a better\nbusiness outlook and the expectation\nthat many of the existing business\nproblems will be solved in the course\nof the next few months are highly\nencouraging to everybody.\u201d said Mr\nSpencer. \"These, together 'with big\ni reductions in federal expenses and\nj putting of more business Into gov\nernment Instead of more government\nInto business, are having a nation\nwide effect. The present administra\ntion will reap the benefit.\u201d\nF. L. BABCOCK.\ni\nj\nj -v i I\nPrices Now\nREDUCED\nEffective at Once\ni\nReduced Prices on\nHupmobile Open Cars\nAnnounced as Follows:\nI I\nStandard Touring Car and Roadster, $1,175\nA Redaction of S4O\nSpecial Touring Car and Roadster, $1,195\nA Reduction of S9O\nAll Prices F. O. B. Detroit; Tax Extra\nHUPMOBILE\nSTERRETT FLEMING, Inc.\nColumbia 5050\nChamplain Street at Kalorama Road\nv Branch New Car Show Room, 1223 Connecticut Are.\nz'\nNew Throws Wrench in Watson\u2019s\nEffort to Win Indiana G. O. P.\nPostmaster General 9 s Announcement\nThat He Backs Coolidge. Seen to\nAugur 111 for Senator\nINDIANAPOLIS. Ind., September\n22.\u2014Hopes entertained by the friends\nof Senator James E. Watson that ha\ncould obtain the Indorsement all\nof the Indiana political leaders In fur\nthering his presidential aspirations\nreceived a setback this weak when\nHarry S. -New, Postmaster General,\narrived here and announced that he\nwill support President Coolidge If\nthe latter Is a candidate for renom-\nInatlon.\nAlthough New\u2019s adherence to the\nCooHtlge cause did not come as a sur\nprise, it disappointed Watson\u2019s\nfriends, who had hoped that they\nmight at least have persuaded the\nPostmaster General to adopt a\n\u201chands-off\" policy. New Is still a\npowerful political factor In Indiana,\ndespite his defeat for renomlnatlon\nby AlbeM J. Beveridge Iff the sena\ntorial primary In 1922. and If he so\nelects he can make things uncomfort\nable for Senator Watson in any at\ntempt to bind the Hoosier delegation\nto the next republican national con\nvention.\nBarks Coolldge.\n\u201cThere Is no doubt whatever in my\nmind but that Mr. Coolidge will be.\nas he very righteously should be, the\nnominee of the party in 1924,\u201d said\nthe Postmaster General. \u201cThat seems\nto have been taken by unanimous\nconsent and approval.\u201d\nThat is all New would say on the\npolitical situation, but to those ac\nquainted with his affairs In Indiana\nit told the whole story of the long\nfeud between the Postmaster General\nand Watson, dating back to the time\nNew defeated Watson in a memorable\ncampaign for the senatorial nomina\ntlon In 1916. It means that New will\nnever subscribe to the Watsonlan\npresidential ambition.\nFOUR SEEK TEXAS\nDEMOCRATSUPPORT\nFord, McAdoo and Under\nwood Booms Under Way for\nForty State Delegates.\ni\nII Special Dispatch to The Star.\nAUSTIN, Tex., September 22.\u2014Cam\npaigns to win the Texas delegation\u2019s\ni forty votes in next year's democratic\nnational convention, on behalf of two\noutstanding presidential possibilities,\nwill be formally launched In Texas\nwithin the next month, while a state\nwide organization has already begun\nwork for a third candidate and the\nfourth possible recipient of the\nTexas delegation vote Is here in per\nson and playing keen political strat\negy in avoiding an indorsement of\nany avowed candidate.\nUnited States Senator Oscar Urfiler\nwood of Alabama, who has announced\nfor the nomination, will visit Austin,\nthe Texas capital, soon. He will be\nthe guest of honor at a banquet\ngiven by his friend. C. N. Avery,\nAustin water and light commissioner,\nattended by state political leaders,\nwhen the Underwood boom in Texas\nwill be officially started. Under-\nIt is recalled that in the winter of\n1920, when a somewhat analogous\nsituation prevailed. New. then .9\nsenator, came out for Warren G.\nHarding. Watson then was casting\nlonging eyes on the nomination, and\nNew\u2019s stand, along with the position\ntaken by James P. Goodrich, former\ngovernor, prevented him from getting\na campaign under way. Observers are\nwondering If a similar situation Is\ndeveloping.\nWill R. Wood, representative In the\nCongress from the tenth Indiana dis\ntrict and chairman of the republican\ncongressional campaign committee,\nmav face a fight for renomlnatlon.\nWilliam F. Hodges, elate senator and\nformer mayor of Gary, has declined\nan appointment to the Indiana public\nservice commission on the ground\nthat he may seek the congressional\nnomination against Wood.\nWood Foe ot Xew'n.\nWood, It is remembered, carried a\nprotest to President Harding against\nNew\u2019s appointment to the cabinet last\nwinter. He was the chief mouthpiece\nof the antl-New crowd at that time,\nalthough before he ceased talking\nabout the Incident he asserted that\nLawrence E Lyons, then republican\nstate chairman, had told him over the\nlong-distance telephone that If New\nwas elevated to the cabinet \u201cthe re\npublican party of Indiana might as\nwell throw the keys In the well and\ngo home.\u201d\nIt was commonly reported that\nWood was acting at the behest of\nSenator Watson\u2019s friends and that\nthe Watson forces had promised to\nsupport Wood for the senatorial\nnomination in 1926 If anything bet\nter was In store for Watson. Much\nbitter feeling was stirred up during\nthe controversy, and today It is ap\nparent that followers of New would\nbe willing to lend every measure of\nassistance to Hodges In a contest\nagainst Wood.\nHAROLD C. FEIGHTNER.\nwood will also speak at the Dallas\nstate fair In October, when he will\nbe heard by more than 100,000 per\nsons.\nLeads Ford Movement.\nFormer Texas Gov. J. E. Ferguson\nof Temple, who has assumed leader\nship of the Ford-for-Presldent move\nment in the State, has called a meet\ning of Ford backers In Austin for\nSeptember 27 and will address the\nmeeting, formally launching the ef\nfort to win the'forty votes of Texas\nfor Henry Ford.\nThe McAdoo Club has been or\ngranized several weeVs, with Marshall\nHicks of San Antonio chairman and\nLarry Mills of Austin secretary. The\nMcAdoo forces claim to be organized\ndown to precincts and that they will\nsweep an Instructed delegation from\nprecinct to county, state and national\nconventions on behalf of their man.\nFormer United States Se\".i.t<T\nJoseph Weldon Bailey of Texas, still I\na power in state politics, has given\na straightout Indorsement of Under\nwood.\nGovernor la SUent.\nGov. Pat M. Neff has carefully re- j\nfralned from any indorsement of a j\npresidential candidate. William Jen- i\nnings Bryan h;V declared Neff is j\nhimself a distinct possibility. Neffs j\nfriends say they will make an effort\nto get a Texas delegation Instructed\nfor the governor and that, further- i\nmore, they will undertake to carry j\nhim to the national convention as j\nthe head of the delegation, saying\nthat this can be done without em\nbarrassment or confusion, so far as\ncasting the vote for him is con\ncerned. They say the delegation will\nbe made up at \u201cNeff democrats\" rep\nresenting the rigid prohibition atti\ntude of the governor.\nNational politics will, during the\ncoming months, transcend the im\nportance of all state campaigns and\nelections.\nS. RAYMOND BROOKS.\n\u2666f Box tad Ac- _ ritoh tiui\ncordoon plaitod 4xl B&N 1\n\u2666f \u2014plain tftd *jfTy*\u00a7 TIT I full and long;\nplaid effect*. P crfoct \u00aekiu*.\ns3*9B s3*9B Xt\ng 7th and H.Sts N.W V O\nu L XX\n\u2666f\nCash Selling Permits Our Selling for Less. g\nSigmund\u2019s Is Famous for\nI Tailored Suits I\n\nx*\n\u25a0_\u25a0 \u2014because we always offer such\nt+ i famously big values\u2014that are seem- XX\n\u2666f ingly beyond the reach of competi-\n5 _V tion. Conspicuous in an assortment %X\n\u2666t V/l\\ |jg| are e\u00dfe t^ree S ra^es t*\nI i|ftW]>) 5iq.75~\n=l= |ny jk A Poirets jU\nh psi If ways I\nH a M-rl U-U Tricotke! H\ni p f\nI S 3\u00abP I\nIn L H\n\nn They are masterfully modeled\u2014on those long, straight lines\u2014that make such\ngraceful costumes for all figures. Tailored with greatest care of the most minute\ndetails. The $19.75 grade durably lined\u2014the other two grades lined with superior silk. X*\nn A Suit is a very essential feature of every woman\u2019s wardrobe\u2014and a Sigmund\niXt Suit is the best she can possibly Buy for the price.\nin n\nH Stout Sizes in Sigmund Tailored Suits\nH I \u2014As large as need be\u2014fashioned with charming grace $90.75 i\nXX and lined with silk\n'tt\nyt\n\nrtr\njj\u00a7>aks i\nPennsylvania Avenue, Seventh Street N\nI i\nAn Offering at an Underprice\nof About\n500 pairs of\nWomen\u2019s Low Shoes\n$5.95\nk\nYou\u2019ll promptly appraise them at the\nhigher prices they are actually worth.\ni 1 ,t\nThey are in the slender toe effects, and\nalso the new French toe style\u2014both lasts\nthat are very popular.\nPatent colt, with two straps and cross\nstraps; plain or with suede trimming.\nBlack satin with one strap and medium\nheel. v\nAll sizes and widths in each of the\nmodels.\nFirst Floor.\n\nu\n.V* 11\nv v\nz r\n7","height":"24879","width":"19605"}}
